WEBVTT

p01
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.111
Open Marketing, then Campaigns.

p02
00:00:03.037 --> 00:00:06.944
This page gathers every campaign the network runs into one list.

p03
00:00:07.695 --> 00:00:10.221
The rest of Marketing sits in the sidebar beside it.

p04
00:00:11.181 --> 00:00:15.252
This whole lesson is look-only, so nothing here sends or launches.

p05
00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:17.050
Start at the top row.

p06
00:00:18.130 --> 00:00:19.814
Four tiles hold the snapshot: active campaigns, messages sent this month,

p07
00:00:20.245 --> 00:00:21.415
average open rate, and revenue attributed.

p08
00:00:21.852 --> 00:00:23.161
Here the numbers are quiet, mostly zero.

p09
00:00:23.698 --> 00:00:34.159
On a live tenant this is your fast read on how marketing is doing.

p10
00:00:34.663 --> 00:00:36.485
Below the tiles, three panels.

p11
00:00:36.755 --> 00:00:38.123
First, Send Volume.

p12
00:00:38.611 --> 00:00:41.911
It draws email and text volume across the last thirty days.

p13
00:00:42.340 --> 00:00:46.641
One glance tells you whether sending is climbing, holding steady, or falling off.

p14
00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:49.221
Next, Campaigns by Type.

p15
00:00:49.629 --> 00:00:51.082
This is the channel mix.

p16
00:00:51.475 --> 00:00:53.888
Most of the network's campaigns go by email, a chunk pair email with text,

p17
00:00:54.206 --> 00:00:59.135
and smaller slices run text-only or push.

p18
00:00:59.539 --> 00:01:02.320
It tells you how customers are actually being reached.

p19
00:01:02.831 --> 00:01:05.346
The third panel, Campaign Performance.

p20
00:01:05.723 --> 00:01:07.406
It counts campaigns by state: how many are active, sitting in draft, or already wrapped.

p21
00:01:07.717 --> 00:01:13.714
A quick pulse on where the work stands.

p22
00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:16.035
Now scroll to the Campaign List.

p23
00:01:16.351 --> 00:01:17.803
One row per campaign.

p24
00:01:18.382 --> 00:01:20.919
Up top, a New Record button to build one, Export to pull the list out,

p25
00:01:21.260 --> 00:01:26.559
plus filters and a search box to find a campaign fast.

p26
00:01:26.960 --> 00:01:28.300
Read across the headers.

p27
00:01:28.597 --> 00:01:32.406
Name, type, and status, then audience, sent, open rate, and revenue.

p28
00:01:32.646 --> 00:01:34.135
Those last columns are the results, and they fill in only after a campaign sends.

p29
00:01:34.527 --> 00:01:42.788
Here they're all dashes, because none have gone out yet.

p30
00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:45.711
Down the status column, four states.

p31
00:01:45.971 --> 00:01:47.614
Draft is still being built.

p32
00:01:47.911 --> 00:01:49.795
Scheduled is set to go out later.

p33
00:01:50.193 --> 00:01:51.674
Active is running now.

p34
00:01:51.994 --> 00:01:53.831
Completed has finished its run.

p35
00:01:54.402 --> 00:01:58.139
You'll see those same four words everywhere in Marketing, so learn them here.

p36
00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:01.147
Look at the two campaigns with an extra chip.

p37
00:02:01.712 --> 00:02:04.760
It reads weather paused, six locations.

p38
00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:10.899
That campaign is held at those sites for weather,

p39
00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:15.227
while its status still reads scheduled or active.

p40
00:02:15.521 --> 00:02:16.832
If a client says a campaign stopped in one town but not another, check this chip first.

p41
00:02:17.347 --> 00:02:20.320
Where the pause is configured is parked for a later lesson.

p42
00:02:20.794 --> 00:02:23.495
Click New Record to open a blank campaign form.

p43
00:02:24.895 --> 00:02:27.085
Across the top runs a set of tabs: details, content, goals,

p44
00:02:27.665 --> 00:02:30.882
delivery, an A B test, and a weather gate.

p45
00:02:31.272 --> 00:02:33.528
We're only here to see the shape of it.

p46
00:02:34.431 --> 00:02:37.115
Do not save.

p47
00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:41.039
The first tab, Campaign Details, holds the basics.

p48
00:02:41.597 --> 00:02:44.235
A name and subject line, the type and mode, a status, a description, and the run dates.

p49
00:02:44.566 --> 00:02:47.387
Mode is worth a look: a single send, or a drip sequence that spreads messages over days.

p50
00:02:48.139 --> 00:02:58.924
Below it, the audience, where you'd attach who receives the campaign.

p51
00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:01.996
Leave the way we came in: click Cancel.

p52
00:03:03.309 --> 00:03:07.457
The form closes, nothing saved, and the list is right where we left it.

p53
00:03:08.566 --> 00:03:14.049
One tab here, Weather Gate, we didn't open, so how the weather pause is set stays parked too.

p54
00:03:14.480 --> 00:03:15.294
Back on the list, two ways to find a campaign.

p55
00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:17.247
Type a name into the search box, or narrow with Filters.

p56
00:03:18.278 --> 00:03:21.568
The footer counts the records and pages through them.

p57
00:03:22.225 --> 00:03:28.670
Export sits up top for pulling the list out, though we won't touch it.

p58
00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:30.581
So that's Campaigns.

p59
00:03:31.038 --> 00:03:32.554
Four tiles for the snapshot,

p60
00:03:32.875 --> 00:03:38.094
three panels for volume, mix, and status, and one list for the campaigns themselves.

p61
00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:42.494
Read a status, catch a weather pause, open the form to learn its shape.

p62
00:03:42.893 --> 00:03:45.419
All of it without sending or changing a thing.

